        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>What limits our sensitivity calculation is the line brightness.  Our requirements are 8.7 mJy/beam (0.75 K) at a spectral resolution of 0.25 km/s within a 0.4” beam.  These spectral and resolution constraints match those of the Band 3 Science Goal.  When estimating line and continuum brightnesses below, we assume that the emission in the previous observations uniformly filled the beams with which they were observed. Therefore we have scaled the flux densities by the areas of the previous observations (generally 1”x1") to the area of our observations (0.4”x0.4”).

Molecular Line sensitivity:
The SO2  transition observed by Klaassen et al. 2009 has a peak intensity of 0.5 Jy/beam (1” beam, see Figure 1). At our resolution,this corresponds to a  peak flux of 80 mJy/beam.   Assuming an ambient density and temperature of 10^6 cm-3 and 300K, a simple excitation analysis (using RADEX) shows that our proposed SO2 transition will be comparably bright.  We will achieve a minimum SNR of 10 in SO2, which could increase if the SMA beam was not uniformly filled.

Ionized Line sensitivity:
H30a (Keto et al. 2008) has a peak brightness of 0.9 Jy/beam in a 1” beam.  Scaling that intensity directly to our beam size, we expect a peak brightness of 140 mJy/beam, corresponding to a peak SNR of 16. Because H28a  is at a higher frequency, we can expect it to be slightly brighter than H30a. From this we can quantify the gas dynamics.

Continuum sensitivity
From Figure 1, the peak flux of the continuum in the SMA beam is 0.5 Jy/beam at 230 GHz.  This scales to 80 mJy/beam in our 0.4” beam.  Assuming the emission is thermal dust in the Rayleigh-Jeans tail (beta=2), the expected flux at 280 GHz is 120 mJy/beam. Further assuming we can find ~ 2000 channels for the continuum (half of the channels in each of the LSB base bands) we will get a continuum sensitivity of 0.5 mJy/beam, giving a SNR of over 200.

Imaging:
Here we propose a mosaic to map the same area as the single pointing Band 3 observations.  The large scale ammonia maps of Sollins et al. (2005) show that there is molecular emission in this region covering the greater part of the band 3 Field of View (almost 1 arc min across).

Correlator Setup:
In this Science Goal we are targeting a radio recombination line (H28a) and three molecular species (CS, SO2 and CH3CN).  Note that we require an entire baseband to get most of the K components of the CH3CN J=16-15 transition, with the highest energy transitions being observed within the baseband devoted to CS.  We will likely be able to detect the K=9 component of the CH3CN K=ladder (see Figure 7 of Klaassen et al. 2009), which is more than 468 Mhz away from the K=0 component (our bandwidth at a spectral resolution of 0.25 km/s).  From the full CH3CN K-ladder we can determine the temperature of the gas using a population diagram (as the k-components are radiatively decoupled, their relative populations directly probe the temperature of the gas when the optical depth is taken into account).  The CS traces the bulk of the (denser) gas in the envelope and the SO2 probes the warm gas directly surrounding the HII region.

There are no special constraints with respect to bandpass accuracy or scheduling, although our data rate is listed as high.

Each of the molecular and ionized species we are requesting are required for our science goals.  Where possible, we have cut down the number of channels to be only half of the bandpass. We cannot cut down the number of channels to 1/4 of the bandwidth because it is unclear how wide our lines will be, and limiting the bandpass to 120 km/s may not given enough channels to (1) find line free regions for continuum subtraction and (2) give enough channels to detect the continuum itself.  For Baseband 3, we require the use of the entire baseband to detect the K-ladder of the CH3CN.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
