        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>What limits our sensitivity calculation is the line brightness.  Our requirements are 2.5 mJy/beam (1.75 K) at a spectral resolution of 0.2 km/s within a 0.4” beam.  These spectral and resolution constraints match those of the Band 7 Science Goal.  When estimating line and continuum brightnesses below, we assume that the emission in the previous observations uniformly filled the beams with which they were observed. Therefore we have scaled the flux densities by the areas of the previous observations (generally 1”x1") to the area of our observations (0.4”x0.4”).

Molecular Line sensitivity:
H2CO was observed towards this source by Araya et al. (2007) at 6cm with the GBT, and had a line peak of 88 mJy.  From a simple RADEX calculation (T=300K), we expect our transition to be only 80% as bright (70mJy).  The GBT beam at 6 cm is 2.5 arc min, and thus we assume the beam is not uniformly filled.  We cannot constrain the beam filling factor, and thus assume instead that the line will have a brightness of 70 mJy in our beam. This results in a SNR of ~35.  We expect the HCO+, H13CO+ and SiO to be brighter than the H2CO.

Ionized Line sensitivity:
H30a (Keto et al. 2008) has a peak brightness of 0.9 Jy/beam in a 1” beam.  Scaling that intensity directly to our beam size, we expect a peak brightness of 140 mJy/beam, corresponding to a peak SNR of 80.  Because H40a  is at a lower frequency, we can expect it to be slightly less bright than H30a, however our sensitivity is sufficient to account for this. From these measurements we can quantify the gas dynamics. 

Continuum sensitivity
From Figure 1, the peak flux of the continuum in the SMA beam is 0.5 Jy/beam at 230 GHz.  This scales to 80 mJy/beam in our 0.4” beam.  Assuming the emission is thermal dust in the Rayleigh-Jeans tail (beta=2), the expected flux at 100 GHz is  15 mJy/beam. Further assuming we can find ~ 2000 channels for the continuum (half of the channels in each of the LSB base bands) we will get a continuum sensitivity of 0.5 mJy/beam, giving a SNR of over 30.

Imaging:
Here we propose a mosaic to map the same area as the single pointing Band 3 observations.  The large scale ammonia maps of Sollins et al. (2005) show that there is molecular emission in this region covering the greater part of our Field of View (almost 1 arc min across).

Correlator Setup:
In this Science Goal we are targeting a radio recombination line (H40a) and three molecular species (HCO+, SiO and H2CO).  Because we expect the HCO+ to be optically thick, we require the less optically thick H13CO+ to trace the molecular gas dynamics closest to the HII region.  The SiO will trace any shock fronts within the system, and the H2CO will trace warm gas near the HII region.


There are no special constraints with respect to bandpass accuracy or scheduling, although our data rate is listed as high. 

Each of the molecular and ionized species we are requesting are required for our science goals.  Where possible, we have cut down the number of channels to be only half of the bandpass. We cannot cut down the number of channels to 1/4 of the bandwidth because this setup will not allow a spectral resolution &lt; 0.3 km/s, required to resolve the kinematics of lines which are of order 2 km/s wide. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
