    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA observation that will investigate how the most massive stars manage to continue accreting material in the presence of an HII region. Somewhere between 8 and 30 Msun a massive protostar produces an HII region. This has long been thought to signal the end of accretion. Yet, stars of up to 150 Msun have been observed. There must be some mechanism through which the star can continue to accrete material in the presence of an HII region beyond 30 Msun. Here we propose to observe the dynamics of multiple ionised molecular species in the massive star forming region G28.2-0.04. With these tracers, we will build up a 3D picture of the dynamics of the gas in the region, which can then be used to compare with models of accretion through the HII region. We propose to observe two RRLs (H40a and H28a) and a host of molecular species (CH3CN, CS, SO2, SiO and H2CO) which trace the warm dense gas surrounding the HII region. We will do this in Bands 3 and 7 at 0.4", including the ACA. From these observations we will determine the relationship between the ionised and molecular gas dynamics, and infer how accretion can continue in the presence of an HII region.</prp:abstract>
